215//*****************************************************************************
219//*****************************************************************************
220//
221// AM_HAL_GPIO_MASKBIT(psMaskNm, n)
222//
223// Entry:
224// psMaskNm is a pointer to the structure type, am_hal_gpio_mask_t.
225// n is the desired bitnumber.
226//
227// Returns ptr to the bit structure.
228//
229// Since the ptr is required as a return value, a macro does not work.
230// Therefore an inline function is used.
231//
232static inline am_hal_gpio_mask_t*
233AM_HAL_GPIO_MASKBIT(am_hal_gpio_mask_t*psMaskNm, uint32_t n)
234{
235 psMaskNm->U.Msk[n / 32] = (1 << (n % 32));
236 return psMaskNm;
237}
238
239//*****************************************************************************
243//*****************************************************************************
244//
245// AM_HAL_GPIO_MASKBITSMULT(psMaskNm, n)
246//
247// Entry:
248// psMaskNm is a pointer to the structure type, am_hal_gpio_mask_t.
249// n is the desired bitnumber.
250//
251// Returns ptr to the bit structure.
252//
253// Since the ptr is required as a return value, a macro does not work.
254// Therefore an inline function is used.
255//
256static inline am_hal_gpio_mask_t*
257AM_HAL_GPIO_MASKBITSMULT(am_hal_gpio_mask_t*psMaskNm, uint32_t n)
258{
259 psMaskNm->U.Msk[n / 32] |= (1 << (n % 32));
260 return psMaskNm;
261}

422//
423// Apollo3 usage of bits [7:6] of a PADREG field:
424// PULLUPs are available on pins: 0,1,5,6,8,9,25,27,39,40,42,43,48,49
425// RESERVED on pins: 2,4,7,10-24,26,28-35,38,44-47
426// VDD PWR on pins: 3, 36 (b7=0, b6=1)
427// VSS PWR on pins: 37,41 (b7=1, b6=0)
428//
429

477//
479// - C bitfields do not provide shift, width, or mask values.
480// - Shift values are generally compiler specific. However for IAR, Keil, and
481// GCC, the bitfields are all exactly as defined in the above structure.
482// - These defines should be used sparingly.
483//

489#define EGPINPUT_S 12
490#define EINTDIR_S 13
491#define UIOMNUM_S 16
492#define UNCE_S 19
493#define ECEPOL_S 21

495#define UFUNCSEL_W 3
496#define EPOWERSW_W 2
497#define EPULLUP_W 3
498#define EDRVSTR_W 2

869#define am_hal_gpio_input_read(n) ( \
870 (AM_REGVAL( (AM_REGADDR(GPIO, RDA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3)) ) >> /* Read appropriate register */ \
871 ((uint32_t)(n) & 0x1F) ) & /* Shift by appropriate number of bits */ \
872 ((uint32_t)0x1) ) /* Mask out the LSB */
873
874#define am_hal_gpio_output_read(n) ( \
875 (AM_REGVAL( (AM_REGADDR(GPIO, WTA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3)) ) >> /* Read appropriate register */ \
876 ((uint32_t)(n) & 0x1F) ) & /* Shift by appropriate number of bits */ \
877 ((uint32_t)0x1) ) /* Mask out the LSB */
878
879#define am_hal_gpio_enable_read(n) ( \
880 (AM_REGVAL( (AM_REGADDR(GPIO, ENA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3)) ) >> /* Read appropriate register */ \
881 ((uint32_t)(n) & 0x1F) ) & /* Shift by appropriate number of bits */ \
882 ((uint32_t)0x1) ) /* Mask out the LSB */

910//*****************************************************************************
911//
912// Note - these macros use byte-oriented addressing.
913//
914#define am_hal_gpio_output_clear(n) \
915 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
916 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, WTCA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) = \
917 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32)))
918
919#define am_hal_gpio_output_set(n) \
920 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
921 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, WTSA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) = \
922 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32)))
923
924#define am_hal_gpio_output_toggle(n) \
925 if ( 1 ) \
926 { \
927 AM_CRITICAL_BEGIN \
928 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
929 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, WTA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) ^= \
930 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32))); \
931 AM_CRITICAL_END \
932 }
933
934#define am_hal_gpio_output_tristate_disable(n) \
935 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
936 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, ENCA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) = \
937 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32)))
938
939#define am_hal_gpio_output_tristate_enable(n) \
940 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
941 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, ENSA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) = \
942 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32)))
943
944#define am_hal_gpio_output_tristate_toggle(n) \
945 if ( 1 ) \
946 { \
947 AM_CRITICAL_BEGIN \
948 ((*((volatile uint32_t *) \
949 ((AM_REGADDR(GPIO, ENA) + (((uint32_t)(n) & 0x60) >> 3))))) ^= \
950 ((uint32_t) 0x1 << ((uint32_t)(n) % 32))); \
951 AM_CRITICAL_END \
952 }

955//*****************************************************************************
959//*****************************************************************************
960//
961// Define Fast GPIO enable and disable.
962//
963#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_enable(n) am_hal_gpio_output_tristate_enable(n)
964#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_disable(n) am_hal_gpio_output_tristate_disable(n)
965
966//
967// Macros for accessing Fast GPIO: set, clear, and read.
968// The 'n' parameter is the pin number.
969// Note - these macros are most efficient if 'n' is a constant value, and
970// of course when compiled with -O3.
971//
972#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_read(n) ((APBDMA->BBINPUT >> (n & 0x7)) & 0x1)
973#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_set(n) (APBDMA->BBSETCLEAR = _VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_SET, (1 << (n & 0x7))))
974#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_clr(n) (APBDMA->BBSETCLEAR = _VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_CLEAR, (1 << (n & 0x7))))
975#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_setmsk(m) (APBDMA->BBSETCLEAR = _VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_SET, m))
976#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_clrmsk(m) (APBDMA->BBSETCLEAR = _VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_CLEAR, m))
977#define am_hal_gpio_fastgpio_wrval(val) (APBDMA->BBSETCLEAR = \
978 (_VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_SET, val) | \
979 _VAL2FLD(APBDMA_BBSETCLEAR_CLEAR, val ^ 0xFF)))
